ated (or the charge redistribution results in NH+)\n\nThis is still fundamentally an electrophilic aromatic substitution, but the product is the protonated form.\n\nThe mechanistic class is: electrophilic aromatic substitution (EAS)\n\nThe reaction center: C:10–C:20 bond formation (new bond between pyrrole C3 and benzylic carbon), with N:14 changing from NH to NH+.\n\nLet me give a compact answer."
